        "excerpt": "King David made a covenant with them before the LORD at Hebron; then they anointed David king over Israel.",
        "body": "The tribes' appeal in verses 1-2 is one of the Old Testament's clearest articulations of the theological basis for Davidic kingship. It is not enough that David is militarily competent or politically astute (though both are true). The tribes ground their request in two things: consanguinity ('we are your bone and your flesh,' 5:1) and divine commission ('the LORD said to you,' 5:2). The first grounds the appeal in covenant-family language — the same phrase Laban used of Jacob (Genesis 29:14) and the men of Judah used of David himself at Hebron (2 Samuel 19:12-13). The second grounds it in prophetic precedent. The tribes are not inventing a new political arrangement; they are catching up to what God already decided.\n\nThe covenant of verse 3 is ratified 'before the LORD' — not merely between human parties but with God as the third party, witness, and enforcer. This places the Davidic monarchy in the category of the Abrahamic and Mosaic covenants, not in the category of political treaty. The king is not sovereign; God is sovereign, and the king is God's steward over God's people. This is the theological claim that makes the Davidic covenant in chapter 7 coherent: God can promise David an enduring dynasty because the dynasty exists to serve God's own purposes, not David's ego.\n\nThe coronation at Hebron is David's third anointing. The first was private, by Samuel, in his father's house (1 Samuel 16:13). The second was over Judah alone (2 Samuel 2:4). This third anointing — over all twelve tribes — is the completion of a divine intention that began two decades earlier. The repetition of anointings is not redundancy; it is the pattern of God's covenantal confirmation, each stage more public and more comprehensive than the last. Charles Spurgeon noted that God rarely gives His people the full inheritance at once; He gives it in installments, each one requiring fresh faith and fresh consecration.\n\nThe summary of verses 4-5 deserves attention for what it implies about the shape of Jesus's ministry. Luke notes that 'Jesus Himself was about thirty years of age when He began His ministry' (Luke 3:23) — the same age the narrator records for David's coronation. The parallel is not coincidental. Luke, the historian among the evangelists, is positioning Jesus as the greater David, entering His public messianic office at the very age the type began his reign.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nagid* (ruler, prince-regent, 5:2) is the distinctive royal title used in 1 Samuel 9:16, 10:1, and 13:14 for the one God has designated. It is different from *melekh* (king) — *nagid* stresses appointment from above, whereas *melekh* stresses the exercise of authority. Both appear in the tribes' speech: God's prior designation (*nagid*) is what qualifies the present coronation (*melekh*). *Berit* (covenant, 5:3) is the standard Old Testament covenant term; its use here deliberately links the Davidic monarchy to the covenant framework of the whole Old Testament."
