        "body": "The Jebusite taunt (5:6) is a measure of how impregnable Jerusalem appeared to ancient strategists. The city occupied the Ophel ridge — steep ravines on three sides, the city's water supply (the Gihon Spring) accessible through an underground shaft. The Jebusites had held it through the entire period of the conquest and judges. Their confidence was so complete that they posted their weakest defenders — the blind and lame — as a theatrical insult. Rashi and the Talmudic tradition (b. Sanhedrin 95a) understood this as a reference to idols, but the plain sense of the text is hyperbolic mockery: 'our city is so secure, the disabled could hold it against you.'\n\nThe capture of the stronghold by David (5:7) is described in one sentence. The narrator provides no tactical account of how the assault was executed — the 'water tunnel' (*tsinnur*, 5:8) has generated enormous scholarly debate, with some identifying it with Warren's Shaft and others with a different water channel, but the text itself is more interested in the theological outcome than the military means. Jerusalem falls. The city that no tribe had taken in four centuries falls to the king who arrives with a divine appointment. The contrast between the Jebusite boast (5:6) and the factual statement of capture (5:7) is the chapter's sharpest theological point: the confidence of opposition to God's anointed is always misplaced.\n\nVerse 10 is the chapter's theological summit: 'David became greater and greater (*halakh gadol*), for the LORD God of hosts was with him.' The title *YHWH Elohim Tsava'ot* — LORD God of armies/hosts — is the military name for God as Commander of heavenly forces. The same title occurs in the Psalms of Ascent (Psalm 46:7, 11; 84:1, 3) that pilgrims would later sing going up to this very city. David's expansion is not a tribute to his own capacity; it is evidence of the divine Commander marching with him. Douglas Moo's observation about New Testament grace applies equally to Old Testament kingship: where God is present, growth is natural; where He withdraws, no human effort can compensate.\n\nVerse 12 records David's own theological interpretation of the Hiram episode: the Lord had established him as king 'for the sake of His people Israel.' This is remarkable self-awareness. The king who has just captured a great city, received international recognition from a major commercial power, and begun building a palace does not conclude that his exaltation is about him. He concludes that his exaltation is instrumental — it exists for the welfare of others. John Calvin notes in his *Harmony of the Historical Books* that this verse is among the most important in Samuel's theology of kingship: it establishes the teleological character of legitimate authority. The king exists for the people; the people do not exist for the king. This is the precise inversion the prophets will later condemn in Israel's corrupt monarchs (Ezekiel 34:1-6) and the precise pattern Jesus embodies as the son of David who 'did not come to be served, but to serve, and to give His life a ransom for many' (Matthew 20:28).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Tsinnur* (water tunnel, 5:8) is a hapax legomenon — the only occurrence of this word in the Hebrew Bible. Its exact referent remains debated. *Halakh gadol* (became greater and greater, 5:10) uses the *halakh* construction to express continuous, progressive action — 'going and becoming great.' *Tsava'ot* (hosts) refers to the heavenly armies of God, not merely earthly military forces — the same armies that Elisha asked God to reveal to his servant's eyes (2 Kings 6:17)."
