        "body": "The narrator places the multiplication of wives and concubines immediately after David's most theologically lucid moment (verse 12). The juxtaposition is not accidental; it is the narrator's way of saying that right theology does not automatically produce right practice. David has just correctly identified that his kingdom exists for Israel's sake. He then immediately acts in a way that the law explicitly prohibited kings from doing. Deuteronomy 17:17 is unambiguous: 'He shall not multiply wives for himself, or his heart will turn away; nor shall he greatly increase silver and gold for himself.' The law is not against marriage; it is against the multiplication that comes with a king's resources and the political alliance-making that inevitably follows.\n\nDavid's multiple marriages are never treated as morally neutral in the Samuel narrative, even when no editorial comment is made. The author of Samuel operates by what Robert Alter calls 'the art of biblical narrative' — the placement of an episode is itself a comment on its moral weight. The list of sons in verses 14-16 includes Nathan (from whom Luke traces Jesus's legal lineage in Luke 3:31) and Solomon (who will surpass David in both wisdom and in the very sin of multiplying wives, 1 Kings 11:3 — seven hundred wives, three hundred concubines). The father's sin becomes the son's catastrophe.\n\nThe most theologically loaded name in the list is Solomon (*Shelomoh*) — a name derived from *shalom* (peace). He appears here as a nameless son among eleven others. But the reader of 2 Samuel 7:12-14 will learn that this Solomon is the specific son through whom the Davidic covenant will be immediately fulfilled. The name dropped casually into a genealogical list carries the weight of the next generation's entire story. Peter Davids notes in his NIGTC work that this technique — embedding a seed of coming narrative in a list — is characteristic of the Deuteronomistic historian, who trusts the careful reader to do the canonical work.\n\nThe passage issues a warning that is more relevant to prosperous believers than to struggling ones: the moment of greatest theological clarity is often also the moment of greatest moral vulnerability. Prosperity and recognition create conditions in which the law feels like an unnecessary restraint on the liberty that success has earned. David at his most theologically articulate is also David at his most practically disobedient. Jonathan Edwards's observation applies: it is not in times of darkness that most believers fall, but in times of light — when they have seen God's faithfulness and wrongly conclude that their own goodness has earned it."
