        "body": "The Philistine campaigns that close chapter 5 are the theological capstone of the whole chapter. Their structure is deliberately parallel and deliberately different: same enemy, same valley, two inquiries, two different commands, two total victories. The parallelism teaches that inquiry of the LORD is a continuous habit, not a one-time event. The difference in the two commands teaches that yesterday's specific guidance does not automatically apply to today's similar situation. Both lessons are essential; without the first, the king acts autonomously; without the second, the king applies the last answer mechanically and misses the new one.\n\nDavid's inquiry formula in verse 19 is the model: 'Shall I go up against the Philistines? Will You give them into my hand?' The double question asks for both direction and assurance — not presuming either. The LORD's answer is specific and unambiguous: 'Go up, for I will certainly give the Philistines into your hand.' The certainty of the promise does not eliminate the necessity of the action; it informs and empowers it. David goes up, defeats them, and then names the place after what the LORD did — not after his own generalship. The name *Baal-perazim* (Master of breakthroughs) is an act of doxological geography. The land itself is inscribed with the record of divine initiative.\n\nThe second battle (5:22-25) is where the chapter's deepest instruction lives. The same enemy returns to the same valley. A king whose confidence had grown through the first victory might reasonably assume that the same direct assault would work again. David does not assume. He inquires again. The LORD's answer is entirely different: do not go up directly; circle around; wait for a specific supernatural signal before engaging. The sound of marching in the tops of the balsam trees (5:24) is the theophanic signal of the angelic host moving ahead of the army — the same invisible armies Elisha's servant glimpsed in 2 Kings 6:17. The LORD goes out before His people to strike; Israel is following behind, not leading in front.\n\nVerse 25 closes the chapter with the obedience formula: 'David did so, just as the LORD had commanded him.' The language deliberately echoes the Pentateuchal obedience statements — Bezalel building the tabernacle 'just as the LORD commanded Moses' (Exodus 39:43), Israel constructing the wilderness camp 'just as the LORD commanded' (Numbers 2:34). The narrator places David in the company of Israel's foundational obedience moments. The king who obeys the divine Commander precisely is the king who inherits the complete victory. From Geba to Gezer — a corridor of twenty miles — the Philistine threat to the central hill country is broken.\n\nCanonically, these two battles anticipate the Messianic battle pattern. The Psalms of Ascent (Psalm 24:8) will ask 'Who is this King of glory?' and answer 'the LORD strong and mighty, the LORD mighty in battle' — language drawn directly from the military experience of 2 Samuel 5. The New Testament applies the same pattern to Christ: the battle against sin, death, and the powers has already been won by the One who goes before (Hebrews 2:14; Colossians 2:15); the church follows behind a Commander who has already broken through.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shaal* (inquired, 5:19, 23) is the standard verb for seeking an oracle from God, the same verb used when Moses sought God's guidance in the wilderness and when the judges consulted the Urim and Thummim. *Parats* (broke through, 5:20) is a violent, rupturing breakthrough — the same root in the name Perez (Genesis 38:29) and the metaphor of a flash flood tearing through a dam. *Ka'asher tsivvahu YHWH* (just as the LORD commanded him, 5:25) is the Deuteronomistic obedience formula, appearing in near-identical form in Exodus 39:32, Numbers 1:54, and Joshua 11:15."
